                            <ul class="prev-next large"><li class="prev"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/1995/11/a-strategy-for-war?lang=eng">Previous</a></li><li class="next"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/1995/11/the-fabric-of-faith-and-testimony?lang=eng">Next</a></li></ul>
                            
                            
                            <h1>
                            Perfection Pending
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/russell-m-nelson?lang=eng"><div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p2" class="">Elder Russell M. Nelson</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div></a>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/russell-m-nelson?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/russell-m-nelson-10.jpg" alt="Russell M. Nelson" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">95911_000_035</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p3" class="">If I were to ask which of the Lord&rsquo;s commandments is most difficult to keep, many of us might cite <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/5.48?lang=eng#47" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 5:48</a>: &ldquo;Be ye therefore perfect, even as your Father which is in heaven is perfect.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote1-95911_000_035">1</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p4" class="">Keeping this commandment can be a concern because each of us is far from perfect, both spiritually and temporally. Reminders come repeatedly. We may lock keys inside the car, or even forget where the car is parked. And not infrequently we walk intently from one part of the house to another, only to forget the reason for the errand.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p5" class="">When comparing one&rsquo;s personal performance with the supreme standard of the Lord&rsquo;s expectation, the reality of imperfection can at times be depressing. My heart goes out to conscientious Saints who, because of their shortcomings, allow feelings of depression to rob them of happiness in life.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p6" class="">We all need to remember: men are that they might have joy&mdash;not guilt trips!<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote2-95911_000_035">2</a>
      </sup> We also need to remember that the Lord gives no commandments that are impossible to obey. But sometimes we fail to comprehend them fully.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p7" class="">Our understanding of perfection might be aided if we classify it into two categories. The first could pertain uniquely to this life&mdash;<span class="emphasis">mortal</span> perfection. The second category could pertain uniquely to the next life&mdash;<span class="emphasis">immortal</span> or<span class="emphasis"> eternal</span> perfection.</p>
			<div>
				<h2>Mortal Perfection</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p9" class="">In this life, certain actions can be perfected. A baseball pitcher can throw a no-hit, no-run ball game. A surgeon can perform an operation without an error. A musician can render a selection without a mistake. One can likewise achieve perfection in being punctual, paying tithing, keeping the Word of Wisdom, and so on. The enormous effort required to attain such self-mastery is rewarded with a deep sense of satisfaction. More importantly, spiritual attainments in mortality accompany us into eternity.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote3-95911_000_035">3</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p10" class="">James gave a practical standard by which mortal perfection could be measured. He said, &ldquo;If any man offend not in word, the same is a <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> man.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote4-95911_000_035">4</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p11" class="">Scriptures have described Noah, Seth, and Job as <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> men.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote5-95911_000_035">5</a>
	</sup> No doubt the same term might apply to a large number of faithful disciples in various dispensations. Alma said that &ldquo;there were many, exceedingly great many,&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote6-95911_000_035">6</a>
	</sup> who were pure before the Lord.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p12" class="">This does not mean that these people never made mistakes or never had need of correction. The process of perfection includes challenges to overcome and steps to repentance that may be very painful.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote7-95911_000_035">7</a>
	</sup> There is a proper place for chastisement in the molding of character, for we know that &ldquo;whom the Lord loveth he chasteneth.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote8-95911_000_035">8</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p13" class="">Mortal perfection can be achieved as we try to perform every duty, keep every law, and strive to be as perfect in our sphere as our Heavenly Father is in his. If we do the best we can, the Lord will bless us according to our deeds and the desires of our hearts.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote9-95911_000_035">9</a>
	</sup></p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Eternal Perfection</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p15" class="">But Jesus asked for more than mortal perfection. The moment he uttered the words &ldquo;even as your Father which is in heaven is perfect,&rdquo; he raised our sights beyond the bounds of mortality. Our Heavenly Father has eternal perfection. This very fact merits a much broader perspective.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p16" class="">Recently I studied the English and Greek editions of the New Testament, concentrating on each use of the term <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> and its derivatives. Studying both languages together provided some interesting insights, since Greek was the original language of the New Testament.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p17" class="">In <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/5.48?lang=eng#47" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 5:48</a>, the term <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> was translated from the Greek <span class="emphasis">teleios,</span> which means &ldquo;complete.&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Teleios</span> is an adjective derived from the noun <span class="emphasis">telos,</span> which means &ldquo;end.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote10-95911_000_035">10</a>
	</sup> The infinitive form of the verb is <span class="emphasis">teleiono,</span> which means &ldquo;to reach a distant end, to be fully developed, to consummate, or to finish.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote11-95911_000_035">11</a>
	</sup> Please note that the word does not imply &ldquo;freedom from error&rdquo;; it implies &ldquo;achieving a distant objective.&rdquo; In fact, when writers of the Greek New Testament wished to describe perfection of behavior&mdash;precision or excellence of human effort&mdash;they did <span class="emphasis">not</span> employ a form of <span class="emphasis">teleios;</span> instead, they chose different words.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote12-95911_000_035">12</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p18" class=""><span class="emphasis">Teleios</span> is not a total stranger to us. From it comes the prefix <span class="emphasis">tele-</span> that we use every day. <span class="emphasis">Telephone</span> literally means &ldquo;distant talk.&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Television</span> means &ldquo;to see distantly.&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Telephoto</span> means &ldquo;distant light,&rdquo; and so on.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p19" class="">With that background in mind, let us consider another highly significant statement made by the Lord. Just prior to his crucifixion, he said that on &ldquo;the third day I <span class="emphasis">shall be perfected.</span>&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote13-95911_000_035">13</a>
	</sup> Think of that! The sinless, errorless Lord&mdash;already perfect by our mortal standards&mdash;proclaimed his own state of perfection yet to be in the future.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote14-95911_000_035">14</a>
	</sup> His <span class="emphasis">eternal</span> perfection would follow his <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">resurrection</a> and receipt of &ldquo;all power &hellip; in heaven and in earth.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote15-95911_000_035">15</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p20" class="">The perfection that the Savior envisions for us is much more than errorless performance. It is the eternal expectation as expressed by the Lord in his great intercessory prayer to his Father&mdash;that we might be made perfect and be able to dwell with them in the eternities ahead.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote16-95911_000_035">16</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p21" class="">The Lord&rsquo;s entire work and glory pertains to the <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/immortality?lang=eng">immortality</a> and eternal life of each human being.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote17-95911_000_035">17</a>
	</sup> He came into the world to do the will of his Father, who sent him.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote18-95911_000_035">18</a>
	</sup> His sacred responsibility was foreseen before the creation<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote19-95911_000_035">19</a>
	</sup> and was foretold by all his holy prophets since the world began.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote20-95911_000_035">20</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p22" class="">The atonement of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> fulfilled the long-awaited purpose for which he had come to the earth. His concluding words upon Calvary&rsquo;s cross referred to the culmination of his assignment&mdash;to atone for all humankind. Then he said, &ldquo;It is finished.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote21-95911_000_035">21</a>
	</sup> Not surprisingly, the Greek word from which <span class="emphasis">finished</span> was derived is <span class="emphasis">teleios</span>.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p23" class="">That Jesus attained eternal perfection <span class="emphasis">following</span> his resurrection is confirmed in the Book of Mormon. It records the visit of the resurrected Lord to the people of ancient America. There he repeated the important injunction previously cited but with one very significant addition. He said, &ldquo;I would that ye should be perfect <span class="emphasis">even as I,</span> or your Father who is in heaven is perfect.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote22-95911_000_035">22</a>
	</sup> This time he listed himself along with his Father as a perfected personage. Previously he had not.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote23-95911_000_035">23</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p24" class="">Resurrection is requisite for eternal perfection. Thanks to the atonement of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, our bodies, corruptible in mortality, will become incorruptible. Our physical frames, now subject to disease, death, and decay, will acquire immortal glory.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote24-95911_000_035">24</a>
	</sup> Presently sustained by the blood of life<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote25-95911_000_035">25</a>
	</sup> and ever aging, our bodies will be sustained by spirit and become changeless and beyond the bounds of death.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote26-95911_000_035">26</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p25" class="">Eternal perfection is reserved for those who overcome all things and inherit the fulness of the Father in his heavenly mansions. Perfection consists in gaining eternal life&mdash;the kind of life that God lives.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote27-95911_000_035">27</a>
	</sup></p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Ordinances and Covenants of the Temple</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p27" class="">Scriptures identify other important prerequisites to eternal perfection. They relate to the ordinances and covenants of the temple.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote28-95911_000_035">28</a>
	</sup> No accountable individual can receive exaltation in the celestial kingdom without the ordinances of the temple. Endowments and sealings are for our personal perfection and are secured through our faithfulness.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote29-95911_000_035">29</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p28" class="">This requirement also pertains to our ancestors. Paul taught &ldquo;that they without us should not be made <span class="emphasis">perfect.</span>&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote30-95911_000_035">30</a>
	</sup> Again, in that verse, the Greek term from which <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> was translated was a form of <span class="emphasis">teleios.</span><sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote31-95911_000_035">31</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p29" class="">In latter-day revelation, the Lord was even more explicit. His prophet wrote: &ldquo;My dearly beloved brethren and sisters, let me assure you that these are principles in relation to the dead and the living that cannot be lightly passed over, as pertaining to our salvation. For their salvation is necessary and essential to our salvation. &hellip; They without us cannot be made perfect&mdash;neither can we without our dead be made perfect.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote32-95911_000_035">32</a>
	</sup></p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Encouragement from the Savior&rsquo;s Example</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p31" class="">Our climb up the path to perfection is aided by encouragement from the scriptures. They hold the promise that we shall, if faithful in all things, become like Deity. John the beloved Apostle wrote:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p32" class="">&ldquo;We should be called the sons [and daughters] of God. &hellip;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p33" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; When he shall appear, we shall be like him; for we shall see him as he is.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p34" class="">&ldquo;And every man that hath this hope in him purifieth himself, even as he is pure.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote33-95911_000_035">33</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p35" class="">Continuing encouragement comes as we follow the example of Jesus, who taught, &ldquo;Be ye holy; for I am holy.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote34-95911_000_035">34</a>
	</sup> His hope for us is crystal clear! He declared: &ldquo;What manner of men ought ye to be? Verily I say unto you, even as I am.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote35-95911_000_035">35</a>
	</sup> Thus, our adoration of Jesus is best expressed by our emulation of Jesus.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote36-95911_000_035">36</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p36" class="">People have never failed to follow Jesus because his standards were imprecise or insufficiently high. Quite to the contrary. Some have disregarded his teachings because they were viewed as being too precise or impractically high! Yet such lofty standards, when earnestly pursued, produce great inner peace and incomparable joy.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p37" class="">There is no other individual to compare with Jesus Christ, nor is there any other exhortation equal to his sublime expression of hope: &ldquo;I would that ye should be perfect even as I, or your Father who is in heaven is perfect.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote37-95911_000_035">37</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p38" class="">This divine entreaty is consistent with the fact that, as begotten children of heavenly parents, we are endowed with the potential to become like them, just as mortal children may become like their mortal parents.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p39" class="">The Lord restored his church to help us prepare for perfection. Paul said that the Savior placed in the Church Apostles, prophets, and teachers, &ldquo;for the perfecting of the saints, &hellip; for the edifying of the body of Christ:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p40" class="">&ldquo;Till we all come in the unity of the faith, and of the knowledge of the Son of God, unto a <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> man, unto the measure of the stature of the fulness of Christ.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote38-95911_000_035">38</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p41" class="">The <span class="emphasis">perfect</span> man described in Paul&rsquo;s quotation is the completed person&mdash;<span class="emphasis">teleios</span>&mdash;the glorified soul!</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p42" class="">Moroni taught how to gain this glorious objective. His instruction stands in any age as an antidote for depression and a prescription for joy. I echo his plea: &ldquo;Come unto Christ, and be perfected in him, and deny yourselves of all ungodliness; &hellip; love God with all your might, mind and strength &hellip; [Then] ye may be perfect in Christ, &hellip; holy, [and] without spot.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote39-95911_000_035">39</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p43" class="">Meanwhile, brothers and sisters, let us do the best we can and try to improve each day. When our imperfections appear, we can keep trying to correct them. We can be more forgiving of flaws in ourselves and among those we love. We can be comforted and forbearing. The Lord taught, &ldquo;Ye are not able to abide the presence of God now &hellip; ; wherefore, continue in patience until ye are perfected.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote40-95911_000_035">40</a>
	</sup></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1995/11/perfection-pending.p44" class="">We need not be dismayed if our earnest efforts toward perfection now seem so arduous and endless. Perfection is pending. It can come in full only after the Resurrection and only through the Lord. It awaits all who love him and keep his commandments. It includes thrones, kingdoms, principalities, powers, and dominions.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote41-95911_000_035">41</a>
	</sup> It is the end for which we are to endure.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote42-95911_000_035">42</a>
	</sup> It is the eternal perfection that God has in store for each of us. I so testify in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
			</div>
		
                            
                            
